The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                                 
	Kuala Lumpur: Rohan Bopanna overcame a one-set deficit to upset world No.51 Jose Acasuso of Argentina 4-6, 6-3, 6-4 and move to the second round of the Malaysian Open while compatriot Somdev Dev Varman bowed out of the Thailand Open, losing to Latvian Ernests Gulbis in the first round.         
	Bangalore: Indias Trupti Murgunde has won the womens singles title at the Yonex Czech International at Brno in Czech Republic. In the final Sunday, Murgunde defeated Jeanine Cicognini of Switzerland 21-17, 21-12.          
	Manchester: Carlos Tevez scored twice as Manchester City outclassed his former club West Ham on Monday to clinch a 3-1 victory in the Premier League. Roque Santa Cruz came on in the second half to make his first appearance after finally recovering from knee surgery.        
	Calcutta: Wasim Akram, one learns, is likely to be present at the Kolkata Knight Riders conditioning camp in Gurgaon, to be held from October 1-8. Akram will join the camp in its latter stages.        
	Johannesburg: The Future Tours Programme post 2012 and the details of the 2011 World Cup would be up for discussion when the ICC chief executives committee (CEC) meets here Thursday. The committee will also talk about a report from the ICC security task force on arrangement of international matches.      
	Calcutta: Australia vice-captain Michael Clarke will return to Australia from the ICC Champions Trophy due to a lower back injury, Cricket Australia said in a release Tuesday. CA had yet to decide on Clarke rsquo;s replacement.      
	Calcutta: Sri Lanka captain Kumar Sangakkara, along with teammates Angelo Mathews, Chamara Kapugedera and Lasith Malinga, met young people affected by HIV at the WITSECHO Adolescent Sprint Holiday Progamme in Johannesburg, Tuesday. The visit formed part of the ICCs THINK WISE partnership with UNAIDS, UNICEF and the Global Media AIDS Initiative (GMAI).                                                                                                                                                                        
